-- BP, Helix Energy, MGM Mirage, Select Medical, SanDisk: U.S. Equity Movers
-- Whitney Kisling
-- 2010-06-14T20:10:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-13/becton-dickinson-fujitsu-sandisk-u-s-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in New York.  
 BP Plc  (BP US) fell 9.7 percent to $30.67. U.S. President
 Barack Obama  wants BP to set up an escrow account to pay the
claims for damages caused by its oil spill in the Gulf of
Mexico, White House adviser  David Axelrod  said. The company’s
board met today to discuss its dividend in light of the leak.  
 East West Bancorp Inc.  (EWBC US) rose 6.8 percent, the most
since Dec. 18, to $16.67. The Pasadena, California-based lender
was raised to “outperform” from “market perform” at Keefe
Bruyette & Woods Inc.  
 Helix Energy Solutions Group Inc.  (HLX US) rose 10 percent,
the most in the Russell 1000 Index, to $11.59. The company was
hired to help BP Plc (BP US) clean up the Gulf of Mexico oil
spill that’s the worst in U.S. history.  
 Lincoln National Corp.  (LNC US) rallied 4.1 percent to
$27.44, the highest price since May 19. The insurer that bought
a lender to qualify for a U.S. bailout said it will sell notes
and stock to repay its $950 million rescue.  
 MGM Mirage  (MGM US) climbed 3 percent to $11.95, the
highest since June 4. The biggest casino owner on the Las Vegas
Strip was raised to “hold” from “sell” at Soleil Securities
Group Inc., which said MGM isn’t overvalued given “signs of
stabilization” in Las Vegas.  
 Las Vegas Sands Corp.  (LVS US), the casino company
controlled by billionaire  Sheldon Adelson , rallied 1 percent to
$25.59. Wynn Resorts Ltd.  
 SanDisk Corp.  (SNDK US) gained 6.1 percent, the most in the
S&P 500 Index, to $47.34. The flash-data storage company is
leading its Silicon Valley peers in boosting profit per
employee. SanDisk earned $684,381 more from each worker last
year than the prior year, according to Bloomberg data measuring
the most recent fiscal year.  
 Select Medical Holdings Corp.  (SEM US) gained 7 percent,
the most since its initial public offering in September, to
$7.63. The hospital operator owned by buyout firms Welsh Carson
Anderson & Stowe and Thoma Cressey Bravo was raised to
“outperform” from “neutral” at Robert W. Baird & Co.  
 THQ Inc.  (THQI US) dropped 12 percent, the second-biggest
decline in the Russell 2000 Index, to $4.91. The publisher of
wrestling and martial arts video games cut its guidance for
first-quarter and full-year results, citing “lower-than-
anticipated” sales of its UFC Undisputed 2010 product and the
strengthening U.S. dollar.  
 To contact the reporter on this story:
 Whitney Kisling  in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net .  
          
          


  
     
       
     
           
                           
                 
                 
                                       
                                   
               
                        
           
